  "en_snotes_asad": "As in verse 99 above - with which this passage connects - the adverb kadhalika (\"thus\") refers to the method and purpose of the Qur'an. Lit., \"as an Arabic discourse (qur'an)\". See, in particular, 12:2, 13:37, 14:4 and 19:97, as well as the corresponding notes. Lit., \"so that they might be [or \"remain\"] God-conscious, or that it create for them a remembrance\", i.e., of God. The verb ahdatha signifies \"he brought [something] into existence\", i.e., newly or for the first time, while the noun dhikr denotes \"remembrance\" as well as the \"presence [of something] in the mind\" (Raghib), i.e., awareness.",
